{"id":"1201.5729","submitter":"Jean-Marie Vanherpe","authors":"Jean-Luc Fouquet (LIFO), Jean-Marie Vanherpe (LIFO)","title":"On Compatible Normal Odd Partitions in Cubic Graphs","comments":"Accepted for publication in Journal of Graph Theory","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A normal odd partition T of the edges of a cubic graph is a partition into\ntrails of odd length (no repeated edge) such that each vertex is the end vertex\nof exactly one trail of the partition and internal in some trail. For each\nvertex v, we can distinguish the edge for which this vertex is pending. Three\nnormal odd partitions are compatible whenever these distinguished edges are\ndistinct for each vertex. We examine this notion and show that a cubic 3\nedge-colorable graph can always be provided with three compatible normal odd\npartitions. The Petersen graph has this property and we can construct other\ncubic graphs with chromatic index four with the same property. Finally, we\npropose a new conjecture which, if true, would imply the well known Fan and\nRaspaud Conjecture\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Jan 2012 09:24:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-01-30"}
{"id":"1201.5730","submitter":"Jonathan Horner","authors":"Jonathan Horner, Robert A Wittenmyer, Jonathan P Marshall, Chris G\n  Tinney and Oliver W Butters","title":"The Curious Case of HU Aquarii - Dynamically Testing Proposed Planetary\n  Systems","comments":"14 pages, 5 figures, 2 tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In early 2011, the discovery of two planets moving on surprisingly extreme\norbits around the eclipsing polar cataclysmic variable system HU Aquraii was\nannounced based on variations in the timing of mutual eclipses between the two\ncentral stars. We perform a detailed dynamical analysis of the stability of the\nexoplanet system as proposed in that work, revealing that it is simply\ndynamically unfeasible. We then apply the latest rigorous methods used by the\nAnglo-Australian Planet Search to analyse radial velocity data to re-examine\nthe data used to make the initial claim. Using that data, we arrive at a\nsignificantly different orbital solution for the proposed planets, which we\nthen show through dynamical analysis to be equally unfeasible. Finally, we\ndiscuss the need for caution in linking eclipse-timing data for cataclysmic\nvariables to the presence of planets, and suggest a more likely explanation for\nthe observed signal.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Jan 2012 09:30:38 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 2 Feb 2012 03:01:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-02-03"}
